Analysis of Effect of Alcohol on Grades of Math and Portugese Language Course¶

Questions¶

How does the overall data looks like? Is it skewed? How is correlation looking between attributes of dataframe? Compare how students grades vary based on the alcohol consumption? How can we predict final grades of students using features that describe students personal and social situations?

Hypothesis¶

We predict that alcohol will have a negative effect on the student’s math and portugese langauge grades. Additionally, we also predict that the number of absences and the amount a student goes out will have a direct correlation with a student’s grade.

Motivation¶

As alcohol becomes more accessible to students around the world due to fake IDs and other forms of fraud, the impact of alcohol consumption on kids’ schooling grows. One of the goals is to spread awareness about consequences of drinking alcholol among teenagers which will help take responsible decisions. In addition, as the world opens up to drinking as a form of a social activity, it is interesting to see whether that opens up alcohol to students as well.

Description of Data¶

The data was collected in secondary schools in Portugal for students ages 15-19 in their Math and Portuguese language classes. The dataset has attributes that consider the student’s upbringing through information such as parent’s job, parent’s cohabitation status, and parent’s education level as well as family size. The data collected tries to create a full picture of the environment in which these students live in and which environments produce positive results in terms of better grades and reduced alcohol consumption. The dataset also considers the social life of students and their socio-economic status and their previous academic performance as attributes to create this bigger picture of who the students are.

Biases/Assumptions/Rationale:¶

There are societal assumptions that alcohol is a substance that negatively impacts education and success. There is also the assumption that weekend alcohol consumption is considered more socially acceptable and this is an attribute that the dataset acknowledges. There are also assumptions that the students that go out more, are going out in an environment likely with alcoholic substances, but going out with friends does not necessarily equate to a time to consume alcohol. There is also a bias that students whose parents do not have much education or high-paying jobs or student’s that do not live in a traditional family context are more likely to get bad grades which is not always the case.

Methods¶

  1. Linear Regression, Multiple Linear Regression
  2. Decision Tree Classifier
  3. K means clustering

Data Content¶

Attributes meaning for 'student-mat.csv' and 'student-por.csv' datasets

  1. school - student's school name ('MS' - Mousinho da Silveira or 'GP' - Gabriel Pereira)
  2. sex - student's sex ('F' - Female or 'M' - Male)
  3. age - student's age (from 15 to 22)
  4. address - student's home address type ('U' - Urban or 'R' - Rural)
  5. famsize - family size ('LE3' - Less or equal to 3 or 'GT3' - Greater than 3)
  6. Pstatus - parent's cohabitation status ('T' - Living Together or 'A' - apart)
  7. Medu - mother's education (0 - none, 1 - primary education (4th grade), 2 - 5th to 9th grade, 3 - secondary education or 4 - higher education)
  8. Fedu - father's education (0 - none, 1 - primary education (4th grade), 2 - 5th to 9th grade, 3 - secondary education or 4 - higher education)
  9. Mjob - mother's job (nominal: 'teacher', 'health' care related, civil 'services'(e.g. administrative or police), 'at_home' or 'other')
  10. Fjob - mother's job (nominal: 'teacher', 'health' care related, civil 'services'(e.g. administrative or police), 'at_home' or 'other')
  11. reason - reason to choose this school (nominal: close to 'home', school 'reputation', 'course' preference or 'other')
  12. guardian - student's guardian (nominal: 'mother', 'father' or 'other')
  13. traveltime - home to school travel time (1 - <15 min., 2 - 15 to 30 min., 3 - 30 min. to 1 hour, or 4 - >1 hour)
  14. studytime - weekly study time (1 - <2 hours, 2 - 2 to 5 hours, 3 - 5 to 10 hours, or 4 - >10 hours)
  15. failures - number of past class failures (n if 1<=n<3, else 4)
  16. schoolsup - extra educational support (yes or no)
  17. famsup - family educational support (yes or no)
  18. paid - extra paid classes within the course subject (Math or Portuguese) (yes or no)
  19. activities - extra-curricular activities (yes or no)
  20. nursery - attended nursery school (yes or no)
  21. higher - wants to take higher education (yes or no)
  22. internet - Internet access at home (yes or no)
  23. romantic - with a romantic relationship (yes or no)
  24. famrel - quality of family relationships (from 1 - very bad to 5 - excellent)
  25. freetime - free time after school (from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)
  26. goout - going out with friends (from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)
  27. Dalc - workday alcohol consumption (from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)
  28. Walc - weekend alcohol consumption (from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)
  29. health - current health status (from 1 - very bad to 5 - very good)
  30. absences - number of school absences (from 0 to 93)
  31. G1 - first period grade (from 0 to 20)
  32. G2 - second period grade (from 0 to 20)
  33. G3 - final grade (from 0 to 20)

General observations about the student-por.csv data:

  1. Most of the variables such as school, address, famsize, Pstatus, schoolsup, famsup, nursery, higher, internet, are skewed towards one value over the other, except for the 'activities' variable.

  2. There are more females than males.

  3. Medu and Fedu have a balanced distribution.

  4. There are more than 50% of the students who take less than 15 minutes to reach school, rest of them take about 15 to 30 minutes or more than 30 minutes to reach school.

  5. It seems half of the students tend to study 2 to 5 hours per week, nearly 200 of them study less than 2 hours per week, and the rest of them are studying more than 5 hours per week.

  6. There are nearly more than approx. 70% students who never failed a course.

  7. Half of the students tends to be comfortable with the family.

  8. freetime and goout share almost similar distribution.

  9. Weekday alcohol consumption is quite minimal.

  10. Weekends alcohol consumption increases, while the group of students who consume or consume little alcohol remains dominant.

  11. Approx. 40% students are in good health.

  12. Many students chose the school due to the course of study, others since it was closer to home, or it's reputation and there are minority who chose it for some other reasons.

Some Observations from the correlation heatmap graph above:

1. There is a strong positive correlation between the 3 grades G1, G2, G3. Meaning if G1 increases, G2 and G3 also increases.

2. There is a weak positive correlation between age and absences. Meaning if age increases, absences increases weakly.

3. There is also a weak negative correlation between age, absences with respect to grades G1, G2, G3. Meaning if age or absences increases, grades decreases.

4. "Medu" and "Fedu" have a strong positive correlation(0.65). As a result it seems like parents tend to have the same level of education.

5. "Dalc" and "Walc" have a strong positive correlation(0.61). Meaning high weekday alcohol consumption leads to high weekend alcohol consumption.

6. "Walc" is moderately correlated with "goout"(0.37). It can be said that people who go out with their friends tend to drink alcohol.

7. "goout" and "freetime" are moderately correlated(0.35). So the number of times a student goes out with friends depends on the amount of free time.

8. "Walc" and "study time" have a moderate negative correlation(-0.22). So students who are likely to spend more time studying drink less alcohol on weekends.

9. "Medu" and "Fedu" have a moderate negative correlation with "traveltime". Meaning if the parents have a high level of education, the student seems to be located closer to school.

10. "Medu" and "Fedu" have a moderate negative correlation with "failures". Meaning if parents have a high level of education, the student tends to fail less in their course.

11. "Medu" and Fedu" have a weak correlation with G1, G2, and G3 grades. Meaning if the level of parent's education increases, the student's grades increases.

12. "studytime" has a weak positive correlation with grades G1,G2 and G3. Meaning if the hours of study per week increases for students, the students grades are more likely to increase.

13. "Failures" is moderately correlated with "age". Meaning older students tend to have more failures than younger students.

14. "failures" has a moderate negative correlation with G1, G2, and G3 grades. Meaning a student with higher grades are likely to have fewer failures.

15. "Dalc", "Walc", and "traveltime" have a weak negative correlation with grades G1, G2, G3.

At this point, we can observe from the boxplots above that the grades are less (i.e. G1, G2, & G3) for students with higher consumption of alcohol. As a result, grades tend to be decreasing as the alcohol consumption increases.

From the observations made from heatmap, it can be notice that students who tend to have more free time are likely to go out with their friends and since going out and workday alcohol consumption have a positive correlation of 0.35, students tend to drink alcohol. Also, as weekend alcohol consumption and workday alcohol consumption have a strong positive correlation(0.61) i.e. high weekday consumption of alcohol leads to high weekend alcohol consumption.

Understanding from the above two sentences, it can be clearly concluded that grades are affected by alcohol consumption and in relate to that weekday alcohol consumption is increased by weekend alcohol consumption and overall consumption of alcohol is likely to happen because students have more time to go out with friends and leading them to drink.

To back up the argument, we can build two seperate dataframes from studentPOR dataframe based on the alcohol consumption but since alcohol consumption is seperated into workday alcohol consumption and weekend alcohol consumption (i.e. 'Dalc', 'Walc'), we can add the values of Walc and Dalc, to calculate the total alcohol consumption. Similarly, we can get total grades by adding G1, G2, and G3. And using these two dataframes we can calculate the mean difference and use it as a part of analysis.

Note, total alcohol consumption will range from 1 - very low to 10 - very high.

Note, total grade will range from 0 to 60.

Since we have calculated total grade and total alcohol consumption of students we want to crate two different dataframes mainly one which has less alcohol consumption and second with high alcohol consumption.

Since the total alcohol consumption ranges from 1 (very low) to 10 (very high), we can use this range in order to create two dataframes. Dataframe with low alcohol consumption will have students whose total alcohol consumption <= 5. Similarly, high alcohol consumption dataframe will consist of students whose total alcohol consumption > 5.

Also we can drop the columns 'G1', 'G2', 'G3', 'Walc', 'Dalc'.

CONCLUSION : Since the mean of total grade for students with lower alcohol consumption is more than students with higher consumption of alcohol (meaning students with lower consumption of alcohol has a better average grades than students with higher consumption of alcohol) and using the result from heatmap shown in above cells where also it was depicted that grades were dropping as the consumption of alcohol increased, we can finally conclude that alcohol is one of the factor from the dataframe affecting the grades of students.

Question: Now is it possible to use the attributes of dataframe that characterizes a student's personal and social situation to predict student's final grade ?

Well, we can predict the grades using the Decision Tree, SVMs(Support Vector Machines), Ada Boost, and Gradient Boosting.

Before we start to predict the final grades, we will assign a numeric value to each attributes of dataframe which were of type objects in order to include them as a part of training model. For instance a binary number i.e. 0 and 1 for no and yes (or yes = 1 and 0 = no for all columns which consists of yes/no) or 1-5 for columns such as 'Mjob', 'Fjob', 'guardian', 'reason'.

In [9]:
studentPOR['school'] = studentPOR.school.replace(dict(GP = 1, MS = 0))
studentPOR['sex'] = studentPOR.sex.replace(dict(F = 1, M = 0))
studentPOR['address'] = studentPOR.address.replace(dict(U = 1, R = 0))
studentPOR['famsize'] = studentPOR.famsize.replace(dict(GT3 = 1, LE3 = 0))
studentPOR['Pstatus'] = studentPOR.Pstatus.replace(dict(T = 1, A = 0))
studentPOR['schoolsup'] = studentPOR.schoolsup.map(dict(yes = 1, no = 0))
studentPOR['famsup'] = studentPOR.famsup.map(dict(yes = 1, no = 0))
studentPOR['paid'] = studentPOR.paid.map(dict(yes = 1, no = 0))
studentPOR['activities'] = studentPOR.activities.map(dict(yes = 1, no = 0))
studentPOR['nursery'] = studentPOR.nursery.map(dict(yes = 1, no = 0))
studentPOR['higher'] = studentPOR.higher.map(dict(yes = 1, no = 0))
studentPOR['internet'] = studentPOR.internet.map(dict(yes = 1, no = 0))
studentPOR['romantic'] = studentPOR.romantic.map(dict(yes = 1, no = 0))
studentPOR['Mjob'] = studentPOR.Mjob.replace(dict(at_home = 1, health = 2, services = 3, teacher = 4, other =5))
studentPOR['Fjob'] = studentPOR.Fjob.replace(dict(at_home = 1, health = 2, services = 3, teacher = 4, other =5))
studentPOR['reason'] = studentPOR.reason.replace(dict(course = 1, home = 2, reputation = 3, other = 4))
studentPOR['guardian'] = studentPOR.guardian.replace(dict(father = 1, mother = 2, other = 3))

At this stage, since the object types are successfully changes to numeric values we will begin predicting final grades of a student 'G3' using studentPOR dataframe.

But before we predict we will disclude attributes that characterize student's career for e.g. absences, failures, G1, G2 because we want to train the model using features that describe the personal and social situation of a student.

In [10]:

y = studentPOR.G3

Result/Conclusion from Decision Tree, SVMs(Support Vector Machines), Ada Boost, and Gradient Boosting:

  1. From the above two bar gaphs and after running all the models multiple times, the mean absoulte error and root mean squared error was less and quite consistent for Decision Tree, Support Vector Machines, and Gradient Boosting compared to Random Forest and Ada Boost which were resulted in significantly higher mean absoulte error and root mean squared error.
  1. The accuracy was ranged from 30-55 for Decision Tree, SVMs, and Gradient Boosting, and 15-35 for Random Forest and Ada Boosting.
  1. Support Vector Machines has lower MAE than the other models.
  1. Ada Boost is the model that showed the worst perfomance, with an MAE = 1.696(Note: this value is most likely to change on running the cells again).

We can conclude by saying that Decision Tree, SVMs(Support Vector Machines), and Gradient Boosting were the best models in the terms of performance.

1. The correlation of "school" with "Medu" and "Fedu" is moderate. "GP" students are likely to have parents with higher levels of education.

4. "higher" have a moderate positive correlation with "G1", "G2" and "G3". Meaning students who want to continue their studies tend to have higher grades.

7. "higher" has a moderate correlation with "Medu", "studytime" and "failures. It can be seen that students who plan to continue their studies are more likely to have a mother with a high level of education, spend more hours studying, and with that they have lesser failures.

import pandas as pd
import sklearn.cluster as cl
import sklearn.metrics.pairwise as pairs

quantDF = mergeDF.drop(['school','address','sex','famsize','Pstatus','Mjob','Fjob','reason','guardian','schoolsup','famsup','paid_x','activities','nursery','higher','internet','romantic','paid_y'], axis=1)
normDF = (quantDF - quantDF.mean()) / quantDF.std()
km = cl.KMeans(n_clusters = 2)
labels = km.fit_predict(normDF)
normDF['CID'] = labels
normHD = pairs.manhattan_distances(normDF.iloc[:, :-1])
normHD = pd.DataFrame(normHD, columns=normDF.index, index=normDF.index)
import sklearn.manifold as mani
mds = mani.MDS(dissimilarity='precomputed')
data2D = mds.fit_transform(normHD)
data2D = pd.DataFrame(data2D, index=normHD.index, columns=['x','y'])
data2D['CID'] = normDF.CID
ax = data2D.plot.scatter(x='x', y='y', c='CID',  s=75, cmap='rainbow', figsize=(12,7))
for i in range(len(data2D)):
    ax.text(data2D.x[i]+0.2, data2D.y[i]+0.2, mergeDF.G1_y[i])

This k-means cluster of the data into two clusters show that higher grades is quite a differentiator in data similarity and that they are two very seperate, distinct sets of data when considering them with little overlap of dots, except a bit in the middle there, but nothing significant enough. Also it seems that there are higher grade in the CID that is higher and more lower grade in the CID that is higher. All in all, this shows that grades from quarter to quarter might be a good differentiator by means to seperate and study the data further since they are grouped together for the most part. The really high grades are really concentrated in sections together which further demonstrates their similarity within themselves.
